long_definition: Self-employed workers are those workers who, working on their own account or with one or a few partners or in cooperative, hold the type of jobs defined as a "self-employment jobs." i.e. jobs where the remuneration is directly dependent upon the profits derived from the goods and services produced. Self-employed workers include four sub-categories of employers, own-account workers, members of producers' cooperatives, and contributing family workers.

indicator_name: Self-employed, male (% of male employment) (modeled ILO estimate)
long_definition: Self-employed workers are those workers who, working on their own account or with one or a few partners or in cooperative, hold the type of jobs defined as a "self-employment jobs." i.e. jobs where the remuneration is directly dependent upon the profits derived from the goods and services produced. Self-employed workers include four sub-categories of employers, own-account workers, members of producers' cooperatives, and contributing family workers.

indicator_name: Employment to population ratio, 15+, female (%) (modeled ILO estimate)
long_definition: Employment to population ratio is the proportion of a country's population that is employed. Employment is defined as persons of working age who, during a short reference period, were engaged in any activity to produce goods or provide services for pay or profit, whether at work during the reference period (i.e. who worked in a job for at least one hour) or not at work due to temporary absence from a job, or to working-time arrangements. Ages 15 and older are generally considered the working-age population.

indicator_name: Employment to population ratio, 15+, male (%) (modeled ILO estimate)
long_definition: Employment to population ratio is the proportion of a country's population that is employed. Employment is defined as persons of working age who, during a short reference period, were engaged in any activity to produce goods or provide services for pay or profit, whether at work during the reference period (i.e. who worked in a job for at least one hour) or not at work due to temporary absence from a job, or to working-time arrangements. Ages 15 and older are generally considered the working-age population.

indicator_name: Time-related underemployment, female (% of employment)
long_definition: Time-related underemployment refers to all persons in employment who (i) wanted to work additional hours, (ii) had worked less than a specified hours threshold (working time in all jobs), and (iii) were available to work additional hours given an opportunity for more work.

indicator_name: Time-related underemployment, male (% of employment)
long_definition: Time-related underemployment refers to all persons in employment who (i) wanted to work additional hours, (ii) had worked less than a specified hours threshold (working time in all jobs), and (iii) were available to work additional hours given an opportunity for more work.

indicator_name: Vulnerable employment, female (% of female employment) (modeled ILO estimate)
long_definition: Vulnerable employment is contributing family workers and own-account workers as a percentage of total employment.

indicator_name: Vulnerable employment, male (% of male employment) (modeled ILO estimate)
long_definition: Vulnerable employment is contributing family workers and own-account workers as a percentage of total employment.

indicator_name: Wage and salaried workers, female (% of female employment) (modeled ILO estimate)
long_definition: Wage and salaried workers (employees) are those workers who hold the type of jobs defined as "paid employment jobs," where the incumbents hold explicit (written or oral) or implicit employment contracts that give them a basic remuneration that is not directly dependent upon the revenue of the unit for which they work.

indicator_name: Wage and salaried workers, male (% of male employment) (modeled ILO estimate)
long_definition: Wage and salaried workers (employees) are those workers who hold the type of jobs defined as "paid employment jobs," where the incumbents hold explicit (written or oral) or implicit employment contracts that give them a basic remuneration that is not directly dependent upon the revenue of the unit for which they work.

indicator_name: Contributing family workers, female (% of female employment) (modeled ILO estimate)
long_definition: Contributing family workers are those workers who hold "self-employment jobs" as own-account workers in a market-oriented establishment operated by a related person living in the same household.

indicator_name: Contributing family workers, male (% of male employment) (modeled ILO estimate)
long_definition: Contributing family workers are those workers who hold "self-employment jobs" as own-account workers in a market-oriented establishment operated by a related person living in the same household.

indicator_name: Employment in industry, female (% of female employment) (modeled ILO estimate)
long_definition: Employment is defined as persons of working age who were engaged in any activity to produce goods or provide services for pay or profit, whether at work during the reference period or not at work due to temporary absence from a job, or to working-time arrangement. The industry sector consists of mining and quarrying, manufacturing, construction, and public utilities (electricity, gas, and water), in accordance with divisions 2-5 (ISIC 2) or categories C-F (ISIC 3) or categories B-F (ISIC 4).

indicator_name: Employment in industry, male (% of male employment) (modeled ILO estimate)
long_definition: Employment is defined as persons of working age who were engaged in any activity to produce goods or provide services for pay or profit, whether at work during the reference period or not at work due to temporary absence from a job, or to working-time arrangement. The industry sector consists of mining and quarrying, manufacturing, construction, and public utilities (electricity, gas, and water), in accordance with divisions 2-5 (ISIC 2) or categories C-F (ISIC 3) or categories B-F (ISIC 4).

indicator_name: Employment in services, female (% of female employment) (modeled ILO estimate)
long_definition: Employment is defined as persons of working age who were engaged in any activity to produce goods or provide services for pay or profit, whether at work during the reference period or not at work due to temporary absence from a job, or to working-time arrangement. The services sector consists of wholesale and retail trade and restaurants and hotels; transport, storage, and communications; financing, insurance, real estate, and business services; and community, social, and personal services, in accordance with divisions 6-9 (ISIC 2) or categories G-Q (ISIC 3) or categories G-U (ISIC 4).

indicator_name: Employment in services, male (% of male employment) (modeled ILO estimate)
long_definition: Employment is defined as persons of working age who were engaged in any activity to produce goods or provide services for pay or profit, whether at work during the reference period or not at work due to temporary absence from a job, or to working-time arrangement. The services sector consists of wholesale and retail trade and restaurants and hotels; transport, storage, and communications; financing, insurance, real estate, and business services; and community, social, and personal services, in accordance with divisions 6-9 (ISIC 2) or categories G-Q (ISIC 3) or categories G-U (ISIC 4).

indicator_name: Labor force participation rate, female (% of female population ages 15+) (modeled ILO estimate)
long_definition: Labor force participation rate is the proportion of the population ages 15 and older that is economically active: all people who supply labor for the production of goods and services during a specified period.

indicator_name: Labor force participation rate, male (% of male population ages 15+) (modeled ILO estimate)
long_definition: Labor force participation rate is the proportion of the population ages 15 and older that is economically active: all people who supply labor for the production of goods and services during a specified period.

indicator_name: Part time employment, female (% of total female employment)
long_definition: Part time employment refers to regular employment in which working time is substantially less than normal. Definitions of part time employment differ by country.

indicator_name: Part time employment, male (% of total male employment)
long_definition: Part time employment refers to regular employment in which working time is substantially less than normal. Definitions of part time employment differ by country.

indicator_name: Labor force, female
long_definition: Female labor force comprises women ages 15 and older who supply labor for the production of goods and services during a specified period. It includes people who are currently employed and people who are unemployed but seeking work as well as first-time job-seekers. Not everyone who works is included, however. Unpaid workers, family workers, and students are often omitted, and some countries do not count members of the armed forces. Labor force size tends to vary during the year as seasonal workers enter and leave.

indicator_name: Labor force, female (% of total labor force)
long_definition: Female labor force as a percentage of the total show the extent to which women are active in the labor force. Labor force comprises people ages 15 and older who supply labor for the production of goods and services during a specified period.

indicator_name: Unemployment, youth female (% of female labor force ages 15-24) (modeled ILO estimate)
long_definition: Youth unemployment refers to the share of the labor force ages 15-24 without work but available for and seeking employment.

indicator_name: Ratio of female to male youth unemployment rate (%) (national estimate)
long_definition: Ratio of female to male youth unemployment is the percentage of female to male youth unemployment rates.

indicator_name: Ratio of female to male youth unemployment rate (% ages 15-24) (modeled ILO estimate)
long_definition: Ratio of female to male youth unemployment is the percentage of female to male youth unemployment rates.

indicator_name: Unemployment, youth male (% of male labor force ages 15-24) (modeled ILO estimate)
long_definition: Youth unemployment refers to the share of the labor force ages 15-24 without work but available for and seeking employment.

indicator_name: Unemployment, female (% of female labor force) (modeled ILO estimate)
long_definition: Unemployment refers to the share of the labor force that is without work but available for and seeking employment.

indicator_name: Unemployment, male (% of male labor force) (modeled ILO estimate)
long_definition: Unemployment refers to the share of the labor force that is without work but available for and seeking employment.

indicator_name: Life expectancy at age 60, female (years)
long_definition: Life expectancy at age 60, female is the average number of years that a female at age 60 would live if prevailing patterns of mortality at the time of age 60 were to stay the same throughout her life.

indicator_name: Life expectancy at age 60, male (years)
long_definition: Life expectancy at age 60, male is the average number of years that a male at age 60 would live if prevailing patterns of mortality at the time of age 60 were to stay the same throughout his life.

indicator_name: Age at first marriage, female
long_definition: Mean age at marriage, female shows the average length of single life expressed in years among those females who marry before age 50. It is a synthetic indicator calculated from marital status categories of men and women aged 15 to 54 at the census or survey date.

indicator_name: Age at first marriage, male
long_definition: Mean age at marriage, male shows the average length of single life expressed in years among those males who marry before age 50. It is a synthetic indicator calculated from marital status categories of men and women aged 15 to 54 at the census or survey date.

indicator_name: Age population, age 00, female, interpolated
long_definition: Age population, female refers to female population at the specified age level. The geographical areas included in the data are the same as the data source.

indicator_name: Age population, age 00, male, interpolated
long_definition: Age population, male refers to male population at the specified age level. The geographical areas included in the data are the same as the data source.

indicator_name: Age population, age 01, female, interpolated
long_definition: Age population, female refers to female population at the specified age level. The geographical areas included in the data are the same as the data source.

indicator_name: Age population, age 01, male, interpolated
long_definition: Age population, male refers to male population at the specified age level. The geographical areas included in the data are the same as the data source.

indicator_name: Age population, age 02, female, interpolated
long_definition: Age population, female refers to female population at the specified age level. The geographical areas included in the data are the same as the data source.

indicator_name: Age population, age 02, male, interpolated
long_definition: Age population, male refers to male population at the specified age level. The geographical areas included in the data are the same as the data source.

indicator_name: Age population, age 03, female, interpolated
long_definition: Age population, female refers to female population at the specified age level. The geographical areas included in the data are the same as the data source.

indicator_name: Age population, age 03, male, interpolated
long_definition: Age population, male refers to male population at the specified age level. The geographical areas included in the data are the same as the data source.

indicator_name: Age population, age 04, female, interpolated
long_definition: Age population, female refers to female population at the specified age level. The geographical areas included in the data are the same as the data source.

indicator_name: Age population, age 04, male, interpolated
long_definition: Age population, male refers to male population at the specified age level. The geographical areas included in the data are the same as the data source.

indicator_name: Age population, age 05, female, interpolated
long_definition: Age population, female refers to female population at the specified age level. The geographical areas included in the data are the same as the data source.

indicator_name: Age population, age 05, male, interpolated
long_definition: Age population, male refers to male population at the specified age level. The geographical areas included in the data are the same as the data source.

indicator_name: Compulsory education, duration (years)
long_definition: Duration of compulsory education is the number of years that children are legally obliged to attend school.

indicator_name: Preprimary education, duration (years)
long_definition: Preprimary duration refers to the number of grades (years) in preprimary school.

indicator_name: Enrolment in pre-primary education, both sexes (number)
long_definition: Total number of students enrolled in public and private pre-primary education institutions (ISCED 0.2) regardless of age. Within ISCED 0, early childhood educational development programmes are targeted at children aged 0 to 2 years; and pre-primary education programmes are targeted at children aged 3 years until the age to start ISCED 1.

indicator_name: Enrolment in pre-primary education, female (number)
long_definition: Total number of female students enrolled in public and private pre-primary education institutions (ISCED 0.2) regardless of age. Within ISCED 0, early childhood educational development programmes are targeted at children aged 0 to 2 years; and pre-primary education programmes are targeted at children aged 3 years until the age to start ISCED 1.

indicator_name: Pupil-teacher ratio, preprimary
long_definition: Preprimary school pupil-teacher ratio is the average number of pupils per teacher in preprimary school.

indicator_name: School enrollment, preprimary (% gross)
long_definition: Gross enrollment ratio is the ratio of total enrollment, regardless of age, to the population of the age group that officially corresponds to the level of education shown. Preprimary education refers to programs at the initial stage of organized instruction, designed primarily to introduce very young children to a school-type environment and to provide a bridge between home and school.

indicator_name: Percentage of enrolment in pre-primary education in private institutions (%)
long_definition: Total number of students in pre-primary education enrolled in institutions that are not operated by a public authority but controlled and managed, whether for profit or not, by a private body (e.g., non-governmental organisation, religious body, special interest group, foundation or business enterprise), expressed as a percentage of total number of students enrolled in pre-primary education. Within ISCED 0, early childhood educational development programmes are targeted at children aged 0 to 2 years; and pre-primary education programmes are targeted at children aged 3 years until the age to start ISCED 1.

indicator_name: Teachers in pre-primary education, both sexes (number)
long_definition: Total number of teachers in public and private pre-primary education institutions. Teachers are persons employed full time or part time in an official capacity to guide and direct the learning experience of pupils and students, irrespective of their qualifications or the delivery mechanism, i.e. face-to-face and/or at a distance. This definition excludes educational personnel who have no active teaching duties (e.g. headmasters, headmistresses or principals who do not teach) and persons who work occasionally or in a voluntary capacity in educational institutions.

indicator_name: Teachers in pre-primary education, female (number)
long_definition: Total number of female teachers in public and private pre-primary education institutions. Teachers are persons employed full time or part time in an official capacity to guide and direct the learning experience of pupils and students, irrespective of their qualifications or the delivery mechanism, i.e. face-to-face and/or at a distance. This definition excludes educational personnel who have no active teaching duties (e.g. headmasters, headmistresses or principals who do not teach) and persons who work occasionally or in a voluntary capacity in educational institutions.

indicator_name: Percentage of teachers in pre-primary education who are female (%)
long_definition: Number of female teachers at the pre-primary level expressed as a percentage of the total number of teachers (male and female) at the pre-primary level in a given school year. Teachers are persons employed full time or part time in an official capacity to guide and direct the learning experience of pupils and students, irrespective of their qualifications or the delivery mechanism, i.e. face-to-face and/or at a distance. This definition excludes educational personnel who have no active teaching duties (e.g. headmasters, headmistresses or principals who do not teach) and persons who work occasionally or in a voluntary capacity in educational institutions.

indicator_name: Primary school starting age (years)
long_definition: Primary school starting age is the age at which students would enter primary education, assuming they had started at the official entrance age for the lowest level of education, had studied full-time throughout and had progressed through the system without repeating or skipping a grade.

indicator_name: Primary completion rate, total (% of relevant age group)
long_definition: Primary completion rate, or gross intake ratio to the last grade of primary education, is the number of new entrants (enrollments minus repeaters) in the last grade of primary education, regardless of age, divided by the population at the entrance age for the last grade of primary education. Data limitations preclude adjusting for students who drop out during the final year of primary education.

indicator_name: Primary education, duration (years)
long_definition: Primary duration refers to the number of grades (years) in primary school.

indicator_name: Primary education, pupils
long_definition: Primary education pupils is the total number of pupils enrolled at primary level in public and private schools.

indicator_name: Enrolment in primary education, female (number)
long_definition: Total number of female students enrolled in public and private primary education institutions regardless of age.

indicator_name: Pupil-teacher ratio, primary
long_definition: Primary school pupil-teacher ratio is the average number of pupils per teacher in primary school.

indicator_name: School enrollment, primary (% gross)
long_definition: Gross enrollment ratio is the ratio of total enrollment, regardless of age, to the population of the age group that officially corresponds to the level of education shown. Primary education provides children with basic reading, writing, and mathematics skills along with an elementary understanding of such subjects as history, geography, natural science, social science, art, and music.

indicator_name: Gross intake ratio in first grade of primary education, total (% of relevant age group)
long_definition: Gross intake ratio in first grade of primary education is the number of new entrants in the first grade of primary education regardless of age, expressed as a percentage of the population of the official primary entrance age.

indicator_name: School enrollment, primary (% net)
long_definition: Net enrollment rate is the ratio of children of official school age who are enrolled in school to the population of the corresponding official school age. Primary education provides children with basic reading, writing, and mathematics skills along with an elementary understanding of such subjects as history, geography, natural science, social science, art, and music.

indicator_name: Over-age students, primary, female (% of female enrollment)
long_definition: Over-age students are the percentage of those enrolled who are older than the official school-age range for primary education.

indicator_name: Over-age students, primary, male (% of male enrollment)
long_definition: Over-age students are the percentage of those enrolled who are older than the official school-age range for primary education.

indicator_name: Over-age students, primary (% of enrollment)
long_definition: Over-age students are the percentage of those enrolled who are older than the official school-age range for primary education.

indicator_name: School enrollment, primary, private (% of total primary)
long_definition: Private enrollment refers to pupils or students enrolled in institutions that are not operated by a public authority but controlled and managed, whether for profit or not, by a private body such as a nongovernmental organization, religious body, special interest group, foundation or business enterprise.

indicator_name: Persistence to grade 5, total (% of cohort)
long_definition: Persistence to grade 5 (percentage of cohort reaching grade 5) is the share of children enrolled in the first grade of primary school who eventually reach grade 5. The estimate is based on the reconstructed cohort method.

indicator_name: Persistence to last grade of primary, total (% of cohort)
long_definition: Persistence to last grade of primary is the percentage of children enrolled in the first grade of primary school who eventually reach the last grade of primary education. The estimate is based on the reconstructed cohort method.

indicator_name: Repeaters, primary, total (% of total enrollment)
long_definition: Repeaters in primary school are the number of students enrolled in the same grade as in the previous year, as a percentage of all students enrolled in primary school.

indicator_name: Primary education, teachers
long_definition: Primary education teachers includes full-time and part-time teachers.

indicator_name: Teachers in primary education, female (number)
long_definition: Total number of female teachers in public and private primary education institutions. Teachers are persons employed full time or part time in an official capacity to guide and direct the learning experience of pupils and students, irrespective of their qualifications or the delivery mechanism, i.e. face-to-face and/or at a distance. This definition excludes educational personnel who have no active teaching duties (e.g. headmasters, headmistresses or principals who do not teach) and persons who work occasionally or in a voluntary capacity in educational institutions.

indicator_name: Adjusted net enrollment rate, primary (% of primary school age children)
long_definition: Adjusted net enrollment is the number of pupils of the school-age group for primary education, enrolled either in primary or secondary education, expressed as a percentage of the total population in that age group.

indicator_name: Children out of school, primary
long_definition: Children out of school are the number of primary-school-age children not enrolled in primary or secondary school.

indicator_name: Children out of school, female (% of female primary school age)
long_definition: Children out of school are the percentage of primary-school-age children who are not enrolled in primary or secondary school. Children in the official primary age group that are in preprimary education should be considered out of school.

indicator_name: Children out of school, male (% of male primary school age)
long_definition: Children out of school are the percentage of primary-school-age children who are not enrolled in primary or secondary school. Children in the official primary age group that are in preprimary education should be considered out of school.

indicator_name: Children out of school (% of primary school age)
long_definition: Children out of school are the percentage of primary-school-age children who are not enrolled in primary or secondary school. Children in the official primary age group that are in preprimary education should be considered out of school.

indicator_name: Lower secondary school starting age (years)
long_definition: Lower secondary school starting age is the age at which students would enter lower secondary education, assuming they had started at the official entrance age for the lowest level of education, had studied full-time throughout and had progressed through the system without repeating or skipping a grade.

indicator_name: Lower secondary completion rate, female (% of relevant age group)
long_definition: Lower secondary education completion rate is measured as the gross intake ratio to the last grade of lower secondary education (general and pre-vocational). It is calculated as the number of new entrants in the last grade of lower secondary education, regardless of age, divided by the population at the entrance age for the last grade of lower secondary education.

indicator_name: Lower secondary completion rate, male (% of relevant age group)
long_definition: Lower secondary education completion rate is measured as the gross intake ratio to the last grade of lower secondary education (general and pre-vocational). It is calculated as the number of new entrants in the last grade of lower secondary education, regardless of age, divided by the population at the entrance age for the last grade of lower secondary education.

indicator_name: Lower secondary completion rate, total (% of relevant age group)
long_definition: Lower secondary education completion rate is measured as the gross intake ratio to the last grade of lower secondary education (general and pre-vocational). It is calculated as the number of new entrants in the last grade of lower secondary education, regardless of age, divided by the population at the entrance age for the last grade of lower secondary education.

indicator_name: Secondary education, duration (years)
long_definition: Secondary duration refers to the number of grades (years) in secondary school.

indicator_name: Theoretical duration of lower secondary education (years)
long_definition: Number of grades (years) in lower secondary education.

indicator_name: Theoretical duration of upper secondary education (years)
long_definition: Number of grades (years) in upper secondary education.

indicator_name: Secondary education, pupils
long_definition: Secondary education pupils is the total number of pupils enrolled at secondary level in public and private schools.

indicator_name: Enrolment in secondary education, female (number)
long_definition: Total number of female students enrolled at public and private secondary education institutions regardless of age.

indicator_name: Vocational and Technical enrolment (% of total secondary enrolment), female
long_definition: Total number of female students enrolled in vocational programmes at the secondary education level, expressed as a percentage of the total number of female students enrolled in all programmes (vocational and general) at the secondary level. Vocational education is designed for learners to acquire the knowledge, skills and competencies specific to a particular occupation or trade or class of occupations or trades. Vocational education may have work-based components (e.g. apprenticeships). Successful completion of such programmes leads to labour-market relevant vocational qualifications acknowledged as occupationally-oriented by the relevant national authorities and/or the labour market.

indicator_name: Secondary education, general pupils
long_definition: Secondary general pupils are the number of secondary students enrolled in general education programs, including teacher training.

indicator_name: Pupil-teacher ratio, lower secondary
long_definition: Lower secondary school pupil-teacher ratio is the average number of pupils per teacher in lower secondary school.

indicator_name: Share of male students in secondary education enrolled in vocational programmes (%)
long_definition: Total number of male students enrolled in vocational programmes at the secondary education level, expressed as a percentage of the total number of male students enrolled in all programmes (vocational and general) at the secondary level. Vocational education is designed for learners to acquire the knowledge, skills and competencies specific to a particular occupation or trade or class of occupations or trades. Vocational education may have work-based components (e.g. apprenticeships). Successful completion of such programmes leads to labour-market relevant vocational qualifications acknowledged as occupationally-oriented by the relevant national authorities and/or the labour market.

indicator_name: Pupil-teacher ratio, secondary
long_definition: Secondary school pupil-teacher ratio is the average number of pupils per teacher in secondary school.

indicator_name: Pupil-teacher ratio, upper secondary
long_definition: Upper secondary school pupil-teacher ratio is the average number of pupils per teacher in upper secondary school.

indicator_name: Secondary education, vocational pupils
long_definition: Secondary vocational pupils are the number of secondary students enrolled in technical and vocational education programs, including teacher training.

indicator_name: Share of all students in secondary education enrolled in vocational programmes (%)
long_definition: Total number of students enrolled in vocational programmes at the secondary education level, expressed as a percentage of the total number of students enrolled in all programmes (vocational and general) at the secondary level. Vocational education is designed for learners to acquire the knowledge, skills and competencies specific to a particular occupation or trade or class of occupations or trades. Vocational education may have work-based components (e.g. apprenticeships). Successful completion of such programmes leads to labour-market relevant vocational qualifications acknowledged as occupationally-oriented by the relevant national authorities and/or the labour market.

indicator_name: School enrollment, secondary (% gross)
long_definition: Gross enrollment ratio is the ratio of total enrollment, regardless of age, to the population of the age group that officially corresponds to the level of education shown. Secondary education completes the provision of basic education that began at the primary level, and aims at laying the foundations for lifelong learning and human development, by offering more subject- or skill-oriented instruction using more specialized teachers.

indicator_name: Gross enrolment ratio, lower secondary, both sexes (%)
long_definition: Total enrollment in lower secondary education, regardless of age, expressed as a percentage of the total population of official lower secondary education age. GER can exceed 100% due to the inclusion of over-aged and under-aged students because of early or late school entrance and grade repetition.

indicator_name: Gross enrolment ratio, lower secondary, female (%)
long_definition: Total female enrollment in lower secondary education, regardless of age, expressed as a percentage of the total female population of official lower secondary education age. GER can exceed 100% due to the inclusion of over-aged and under-aged students because of early or late school entrance and grade repetition.

indicator_name: Gross enrolment ratio, lower secondary, male (%)
long_definition: Total male enrollment in lower secondary education, regardless of age, expressed as a percentage of the total male population of official lower secondary education age. GER can exceed 100% due to the inclusion of over-aged and under-aged students because of early or late school entrance and grade repetition.

indicator_name: Gross enrolment ratio, upper secondary, both sexes (%)
long_definition: Total enrollment in upper secondary education, regardless of age, expressed as a percentage of the total population of official upper secondary education age.

indicator_name: Gross enrolment ratio, upper secondary, female (%)
long_definition: Total female enrollment in upper secondary education, regardless of age, expressed as a percentage of the female population of official upper secondary education age.

indicator_name: Gross enrolment ratio, upper secondary, male (%)
long_definition: Total male enrollment in upper secondary education, regardless of age, expressed as a percentage of the male population of official upper secondary education age.

indicator_name: School enrollment, secondary (% net)
long_definition: Net enrollment rate is the ratio of children of official school age who are enrolled in school to the population of the corresponding official school age. Secondary education completes the provision of basic education that began at the primary level, and aims at laying the foundations for lifelong learning and human development, by offering more subject- or skill-oriented instruction using more specialized teachers.

indicator_name: School enrollment, secondary, private (% of total secondary)
long_definition: Private enrollment refers to pupils or students enrolled in institutions that are not operated by a public authority but controlled and managed, whether for profit or not, by a private body such as a nongovernmental organization, religious body, special interest group, foundation or business enterprise.

indicator_name: Progression to secondary school (%)
long_definition: Progression to secondary school refers to the number of new entrants to the first grade of secondary school in a given year as a percentage of the number of students enrolled in the final grade of primary school in the previous year (minus the number of repeaters from the last grade of primary education in the given year).

indicator_name: Secondary education, teachers
long_definition: Secondary education teachers includes full-time and part-time teachers.

indicator_name: Secondary education, teachers, female
long_definition: Secondary education teachers includes full-time and part-time teachers.

indicator_name: Adolescents out of school, female (% of female lower secondary school age)
long_definition: Adolescents out of school are the percentage of lower secondary school age adolescents who are not enrolled in school.

indicator_name: Adolescents out of school, male (% of male lower secondary school age)
long_definition: Adolescents out of school are the percentage of lower secondary school age adolescents who are not enrolled in school.

indicator_name: Adolescents out of school (% of lower secondary school age)
long_definition: Adolescents out of school are the percentage of lower secondary school age adolescents who are not enrolled in school.

indicator_name: Gross graduation ratio from first degree programmes (ISCED 6 and 7) in tertiary education, female (%)
long_definition: Number of female graduates from first degree programmes (at ISCED 6 and 7) expressed as a percentage of the female population of the theoretical graduation age of the most common first degree programme.

indicator_name: Gross graduation ratio from first degree programmes (ISCED 6 and 7) in tertiary education, male (%)
long_definition: Number of male graduates from first degree programmes (at ISCED 6 and 7) expressed as a percentage of the male population of the theoretical graduation age of the most common first degree programme.

indicator_name: Gross graduation ratio from first degree programmes (ISCED 6 and 7) in tertiary education, both sexes (%)
long_definition: Number of graduates from first degree programmes (at ISCED 6 and 7) expressed as a percentage of the population of the theoretical graduation age of the most common first degree programme.

indicator_name: Enrolment in tertiary education, all programmes, both sexes (number)
long_definition: The total number of students enrolled at public and private tertiary education institutions.

indicator_name: Enrolment in tertiary education, all programmes, female (number)
long_definition: The total number of female students enrolled at public and private tertiary education institutions.

indicator_name: Pupil-teacher ratio, tertiary
long_definition: Tertiary school pupil-teacher ratio is the average number of pupils per teacher in tertiary school.

indicator_name: School enrollment, tertiary (% gross)
long_definition: Gross enrollment ratio is the ratio of total enrollment, regardless of age, to the population of the age group that officially corresponds to the level of education shown. Tertiary education, whether or not to an advanced research qualification, normally requires, as a minimum condition of admission, the successful completion of education at the secondary level.

indicator_name: Percentage of graduates from tertiary education graduating from Agriculture, Forestry, Fisheries and Veterinary programmes, both sexes (%)
long_definition: Share of all tertiary graduates who completed Agriculture, Forestry, Fisheries and Veterinary programmes in the reference year.

indicator_name: Percentage of graduates from tertiary education graduating from Education programmes, both sexes (%)
long_definition: Share of all tertiary graduates who completed education programmes in the reference year.

indicator_name: Percentage of graduates from tertiary education graduating from Engineering, Manufacturing and Construction programmes, both sexes (%)
long_definition: Share of all tertiary graduates who completed engineering, manufacturing and construction programmes in the reference year.

indicator_name: Female share of graduates in Agriculture, Forestry, Fisheries and Veterinary programmes, tertiary (%)
long_definition: Female share of graduates in the given field of education, tertiary is the number of female graduates expressed as a percentage of the total number of graduates in the given field of education from tertiary education.

indicator_name: Female share of graduates in Education programmes, tertiary (%)
long_definition: Female share of graduates in the given field of education, tertiary is the number of female graduates expressed as a percentage of the total number of graduates in the given field of education from tertiary education.

indicator_name: Female share of graduates in Engineering, Manufacturing and Construction programmes, tertiary (%)
long_definition: Female share of graduates in the given field of education, tertiary is the number of female graduates expressed as a percentage of the total number of graduates in the given field of education from tertiary education.

indicator_name: Female share of graduates in Health and Welfare programmes, tertiary (%)
long_definition: Female share of graduates in the given field of education, tertiary is the number of female graduates expressed as a percentage of the total number of graduates in the given field of education from tertiary education.

indicator_name: Female share of graduates in Arts and Humanities programmes, tertiary (%)
long_definition: Female share of graduates in the given field of education, tertiary is the number of female graduates expressed as a percentage of the total number of graduates in the given field of education from tertiary education.

indicator_name: Female share of graduates in Natural Sciences, Mathematics and Statistics programmes, tertiary (%)
long_definition: Female share of graduates in the given field of education, tertiary is the number of female graduates expressed as a percentage of the total number of graduates in the given field of education from tertiary education.

indicator_name: Female share of graduates from Science, Technology, Engineering and Mathematics (STEM) programmes, tertiary (%)
long_definition: Female share of graduates in the given field of education, tertiary is the number of female graduates expressed as a percentage of the total number of graduates in the given field of education from tertiary education.

indicator_name: Female share of graduates in Social Sciences, Journalism and Information programmes, tertiary (%)
long_definition: Female share of graduates in the given field of education, tertiary is the number of female graduates expressed as a percentage of the total number of graduates in the given field of education from tertiary education.

indicator_name: Female share of graduates in Services programmes, tertiary (%)
long_definition: Female share of graduates in the given field of education, tertiary is the number of female graduates expressed as a percentage of the total number of graduates in the given field of education from tertiary education.

indicator_name: Percentage of graduates from tertiary education graduating from Health and Welfare programmes, both sexes (%)
long_definition: Share of all tertiary graduates who completed health and welfare programmes in the reference year.

indicator_name: Percentage of graduates from tertiary education graduating from Arts and Humanities programmes, both sexes (%)
long_definition: Share of all tertiary graduates who completed humanities and arts programmes in the reference year.

indicator_name: Percentage of graduates from tertiary education graduating from programmes in unspecified fields, both sexes (%)
long_definition: Share of all tertiary graduates who completed programmes in unspecified fields in the reference year.

indicator_name: Percentage of graduates from tertiary education graduating from Natural Sciences, Mathematics and Statistics programmes, both sexes (%)
long_definition: Share of all tertiary graduates who completed Natural Sciences, Mathematics and Statistics programmes in the reference year.

indicator_name: Percentage of graduates from tertiary education graduating from Social Sciences, Journalism and Information programmes, both sexes (%)
long_definition: Share of all tertiary graduates who completed Social Sciences, Journalism and Information programmes in the reference year.

indicator_name: Percentage of graduates from tertiary education graduating from Services programmes, both sexes (%)
long_definition: Share of all tertiary graduates who completed services programmes in the reference year.

indicator_name: Percentage of enrolment in tertiary education in private institutions (%)
long_definition: Total number of students in tertiary education enrolled in institutions that are not operated by a public authority but controlled and managed, whether for profit or not, by a private body (e.g., non-governmental organisation, religious body, special interest group, foundation or business enterprise), expressed as a percentage of total number of students enrolled in tertiary education.

indicator_name: Teachers in tertiary education programmes, both sexes (number)
long_definition: Total number of teachers in public and private tertiary education institutions (ISCED 5-8). Teachers are persons employed full time or part time in an official capacity to guide and direct the learning experience of pupils and students, irrespective of their qualifications or the delivery mechanism, i.e. face-to-face and/or at a distance. This definition excludes educational personnel who have no active teaching duties (e.g. headmasters, headmistresses or principals who do not teach) and persons who work occasionally or in a voluntary capacity in educational institutions.

indicator_name: Teachers in tertiary education programmes, female (number)
long_definition: Total number of female teachers in public and private tertiary education institutions (ISCED 5-8). Teachers are persons employed full time or part time in an official capacity to guide and direct the learning experience of pupils and students, irrespective of their qualifications or the delivery mechanism, i.e. face-to-face and/or at a distance. This definition excludes educational personnel who have no active teaching duties (e.g. headmasters, headmistresses or principals who do not teach) and persons who work occasionally or in a voluntary capacity in educational institutions.

indicator_name: Tertiary education, academic staff (% female)
long_definition: Tertiary education, academic staff (% female) is the share of female academic staff in tertiary education.

indicator_name: Gross enrolment ratio, primary to tertiary, both sexes (%)
long_definition: Total enrollment in primary, secondary and tertiary education, regardless of age, expressed as a percentage of the total population of primary school age, secondary school age, and the five-year age group following on from secondary school leaving. GER can exceed 100% due to the inclusion of over-aged and under-aged students because of early or late school entrance and grade repetition.

indicator_name: Current education expenditure, primary (% of total expenditure in primary public institutions)
long_definition: Current expenditure is expressed as a percentage of direct expenditure in public educational institutions (instructional and non-instructional) of the specified level of education. Financial aid to students and other transfers are excluded from direct expenditure. Current expenditure is consumed within the current year and would have to be renewed if needed in the following year. It includes staff compensation and current expenditure other than for staff compensation (ex. on teaching materials, ancillary services and administration).

indicator_name: Current education expenditure, secondary (% of total expenditure in secondary public institutions)
long_definition: Current expenditure is expressed as a percentage of direct expenditure in public educational institutions (instructional and non-instructional) of the specified level of education. Financial aid to students and other transfers are excluded from direct expenditure. Current expenditure is consumed within the current year and would have to be renewed if needed in the following year. It includes staff compensation and current expenditure other than for staff compensation (ex. on teaching materials, ancillary services and administration).

indicator_name: Current education expenditure, tertiary (% of total expenditure in tertiary public institutions)
long_definition: Current expenditure is expressed as a percentage of direct expenditure in public educational institutions (instructional and non-instructional) of the specified level of education. Financial aid to students and other transfers are excluded from direct expenditure. Current expenditure is consumed within the current year and would have to be renewed if needed in the following year. It includes staff compensation and current expenditure other than for staff compensation (ex. on teaching materials, ancillary services and administration).

indicator_name: Current education expenditure, total (% of total expenditure in public institutions)
long_definition: Current expenditure is expressed as a percentage of direct expenditure in public educational institutions (instructional and non-instructional) of the specified level of education. Financial aid to students and other transfers are excluded from direct expenditure. Current expenditure is consumed within the current year and would have to be renewed if needed in the following year. It includes staff compensation and current expenditure other than for staff compensation (ex. on teaching materials, ancillary services and administration).

indicator_name: Current expenditure as % of total expenditure in public institutions (%)
long_definition: Current expenditure expressed as a percentage of direct expenditure in public educational institutions (instructional and non-instructional). Financial aid to students and other transfers are excluded from direct expenditure. Current expenditure is consumed within the current year and would have to be renewed if needed in the following year. It includes staff compensation and current expenditure other than for staff compensation (ex. on teaching materials, ancillary services and administration). Divide all current expenditure in public institutions by total expenditure (current and capital) in public institutions, and multiply by 100. For more information, consult the UNESCO Institute of Statistics website: http://www.uis.unesco.org/Education/

indicator_name: Government expenditure per student, primary (% of GDP per capita)
long_definition: Government expenditure per student is the average general government expenditure (current, capital, and transfers) per student in the given level of education, expressed as a percentage of GDP per capita.

indicator_name: Expenditure on primary education (% of government expenditure on education)
long_definition: Expenditure on primary education is expressed as a percentage of total general government expenditure on education. General government usually refers to local, regional and central governments.

indicator_name: Government expenditure per student, secondary (% of GDP per capita)
long_definition: Government expenditure per student is the average general government expenditure (current, capital, and transfers) per student in the given level of education, expressed as a percentage of GDP per capita.

indicator_name: Expenditure on secondary education (% of government expenditure on education)
long_definition: Expenditure on secondary education is expressed as a percentage of total general government expenditure on education. General government usually refers to local, regional and central governments.

indicator_name: Government expenditure per student, tertiary (% of GDP per capita)
long_definition: Government expenditure per student is the average general government expenditure (current, capital, and transfers) per student in the given level of education, expressed as a percentage of GDP per capita.

indicator_name: Expenditure on tertiary education (% of government expenditure on education)
long_definition: Expenditure on tertiary education is expressed as a percentage of total general government expenditure on education. General government usually refers to local, regional and central governments.

indicator_name: Government expenditure on education, total (% of government expenditure)
long_definition: General government expenditure on education (current, capital, and transfers) is expressed as a percentage of total general government expenditure on all sectors (including health, education, social services, etc.). It includes expenditure funded by transfers from international sources to government. General government usually refers to local, regional and central governments.

indicator_name: Government expenditure on education, total (% of GDP)
long_definition: General government expenditure on education (current, capital, and transfers) is expressed as a percentage of GDP. It includes expenditure funded by transfers from international sources to government. General government usually refers to local, regional and central governments.

long_definition: Number of deaths of children ages 5-9 years

indicator_name: Number of deaths ages 10-14 years
long_definition: Number of deaths of adolescents ages 10-14 years

indicator_name: Number of deaths ages 15-19 years
long_definition: Number of deaths of adolescents ages 15-19 years

indicator_name: Number of deaths ages 20-24 years
long_definition: Number of deaths of youths ages 20-24 years

indicator_name: Probability of dying among children ages 5-9 years (per 1,000)
long_definition: Probability of dying between age 5-9 years of age expressed per 1,000 children aged 5, if subject to age-specific mortality rates of the specified year.

indicator_name: Probability of dying among adolescents ages 10-14 years (per 1,000)
long_definition: Probability of dying between age 10-14 years of age expressed per 1,000 adolescents age 10, if subject to age-specific mortality rates of the specified year.

indicator_name: Probability of dying among adolescents ages 15-19 years (per 1,000)
long_definition: Probability of dying between age 15-19 years of age expressed per 1,000 adolescents age 15, if subject to age-specific mortality rates of the specified year.

indicator_name: Probability of dying among youth ages 20-24 years (per 1,000)
long_definition: Probability of dying between age 20-24 years of age expressed per 1,000 youths age 20, if subject to age-specific mortality rates of the specified year.

indicator_name: Labor force, total
long_definition: Labor force comprises people ages 15 and older who supply labor for the production of goods and services during a specified period. It includes people who are currently employed and people who are unemployed but seeking work as well as first-time job-seekers. Not everyone who works is included, however. Unpaid workers, family workers, and students are often omitted, and some countries do not count members of the armed forces. Labor force size tends to vary during the year as seasonal workers enter and leave.

indicator_name: Unemployment, total (% of total labor force) (modeled ILO estimate)
long_definition: Unemployment refers to the share of the labor force that is without work but available for and seeking employment.

indicator_name: Official entrance age to compulsory education (years)
long_definition: Official age when students should enter compulsory education assuming they start at the official entrance age for the lowest level of education, study full-time throughout and progressed through the system without repeating or skipping a grade. The theoretical entrance age to a given programme or level is typically, but not always, the most common entrance age.

indicator_name: Enrolment in lower secondary education, both sexes (number)
long_definition: Total number of students enrolled in public and private lower secondary education institutions regardless of age.

indicator_name: Enrolment in lower secondary education, female (number)
long_definition: Total number of female students enrolled in public and private lower secondary education institutions regardless of age.

indicator_name: Enrolment in upper secondary education, both sexes (number)
long_definition: Total number of students enrolled in public and private upper secondary education institutions regardless of age.

indicator_name: Enrolment in upper secondary education, female (number)
long_definition: Total number of female students enrolled in public and private upper secondary education institutions regardless of age.

indicator_name: Enrolment in post-secondary non-tertiary education, both sexes (number)
long_definition: Total number of students enrolled in public and private post-secondary non-tertiary education institutions regardless of age.

indicator_name: Enrolment in post-secondary non-tertiary education, female (number)
long_definition: Total number of female students enrolled in public and private post-secondary non-tertiary education institutions regardless of age.

indicator_name: Enrolment in tertiary education, ISCED 8 programmes, both sexes (number)
long_definition: Total number of students enrolled in public and private tertiary education institutions in programmes on the doctoral or equivalent (ISCED 8) level.

indicator_name: Enrolment in tertiary education, ISCED 8 programmes, female (number)
long_definition: Total number of female students enrolled in public and private tertiary education institutions in programmes on the doctoral or equivalent (ISCED 8) level.

indicator_name: Female share of graduates in Business, Administration and Law programmes, tertiary (%)
long_definition: Female share of graduates in the given field of education, tertiary is the number of female graduates expressed as a percentage of the total number of graduates in the given field of education from tertiary education.

indicator_name: Female share of graduates in Information and Communication Technologies programmes, tertiary (%)
long_definition: Female share of graduates in the given field of education, tertiary is the number of female graduates expressed as a percentage of the total number of graduates in the given field of education from tertiary education.

indicator_name: Female share of graduates in other fields than Science, Technology, Engineering and Mathematics programmes, tertiary (%)
long_definition: Female share of graduates in the given field of education, tertiary is the number of female graduates expressed as a percentage of the total number of graduates in the given field of education from tertiary education.

indicator_name: Percentage of teachers in lower secondary education who are female (%)
long_definition: Number of female teachers at the lower secondary level expressed as a percentage of the total number of teachers (male and female) at the lower secondary level in a given school year. Teachers are persons employed full time or part time in an official capacity to guide and direct the learning experience of pupils and students, irrespective of their qualifications or the delivery mechanism, i.e. face-to-face and/or at a distance. This definition excludes educational personnel who have no active teaching duties (e.g. headmasters, headmistresses or principals who do not teach) and persons who work occasionally or in a voluntary capacity in educational institutions.

indicator_name: Percentage of teachers in upper secondary education who are female (%)
long_definition: Number of female teachers at the upper secondary level expressed as a percentage of the total number of teachers (male and female) at the upper secondary level in a given school year. Teachers are persons employed full time or part time in an official capacity to guide and direct the learning experience of pupils and students, irrespective of their qualifications or the delivery mechanism, i.e. face-to-face and/or at a distance. This definition excludes educational personnel who have no active teaching duties (e.g. headmasters, headmistresses or principals who do not teach) and persons who work occasionally or in a voluntary capacity in educational institutions.

indicator_name: Gross enrolment ratio, primary and secondary, both sexes (%)
long_definition: Total enrollment in primary and secondary education, regardless of age, expressed as a percentage of the total population of official primary and secondary education age. GER can exceed 100% due to the inclusion of over-aged and under-aged students because of early or late school entrance and grade repetition.

indicator_name: Gross enrolment ratio, primary and secondary, female (%)
long_definition: Total female enrollment in primary and secondary education, regardless of age, expressed as a percentage of the total female population of official primary and secondary education age. GER can exceed 100% due to the inclusion of over-aged and under-aged students because of early or late school entrance and grade repetition.

indicator_name: Gross enrolment ratio, primary and secondary, male (%)
long_definition: Total male enrollment in primary and secondary education, regardless of age, expressed as a percentage of the total male population of official primary and secondary education age. GER can exceed 100% due to the inclusion of over-aged and under-aged students because of early or late school entrance and grade repetition.

indicator_name: Gross enrolment ratio, primary to tertiary, female (%)
long_definition: Total female enrollment in primary, secondary and tertiary education, regardless of age, expressed as a percentage of the total female population of primary school age, secondary school age, and the five-year age group following on from secondary school leaving. GER can exceed 100% due to the inclusion of over-aged and under-aged students because of early or late school entrance and grade repetition.

indicator_name: Gross enrolment ratio, primary to tertiary, gender parity index (GPI)
long_definition: Ratio of female gross enrolment ratio for primary to tertiary to the male value for the same indicator. It is calculated by dividing the female value for the indicator by the male value for the indicator. A GPI equal to 1 indicates parity between females and males. In general, a value less than 1 indicates disparity in favor of males and a value greater than 1 indicates disparity in favor of females.

indicator_name: Gross enrolment ratio, primary to tertiary, male (%)
long_definition: Total male enrollment in primary, secondary and tertiary education, regardless of age, expressed as a percentage of the total male population of primary school age, secondary school age, and the five-year age group following on from secondary school leaving. GER can exceed 100% due to the inclusion of over-aged and under-aged students because of early or late school entrance and grade repetition.

indicator_name: Gross enrolment ratio, lower secondary, gender parity index (GPI)
long_definition: Ratio of female gross enrolment ratio for lower secondary to the male gross enrolment ratio for lower secondary. It is calculated by dividing the female value for the indicator by the male value for the indicator. A GPI equal to 1 indicates parity between females and males. In general, a value less than 1 indicates disparity in favor of males and a value greater than 1 indicates disparity in favor of females.

indicator_name: Gross enrolment ratio, upper secondary, gender parity index (GPI)
long_definition: Ratio of female gross enrolment ratio for upper secondary to the male gross enrolment ratio for upper secondary. It is calculated by dividing the female value for the indicator by the male value for the indicator. A GPI equal to 1 indicates parity between females and males. In general, a value less than 1 indicates disparity in favor of males and a value greater than 1 indicates disparity in favor of females.

indicator_name: Gross graduation ratio from first degree programmes (ISCED 6 and 7) in tertiary education, gender parity index (GPI)
long_definition: Ratio of female gross graduation ratio to the male value for the same indicator. It is calculated by dividing the female value for the indicator by the male value for the indicator. A GPI equal to 1 indicates parity between females and males. In general, a value less than 1 indicates disparity in favor of males and a value greater than 1 indicates disparity in favor of females.

indicator_name: Share of all students in upper secondary education enrolled in vocational programmes (%)
long_definition: Total number of students enrolled in vocational programmes at the upper secondary education level, expressed as a percentage of the total number of students enrolled in all programmes (vocational and general) at the upper secondary level. Vocational education is designed for learners to acquire the knowledge, skills and competencies specific to a particular occupation or trade or class of occupations or trades. Vocational education may have work-based components (e.g. apprenticeships). Successful completion of such programmes leads to labour-market relevant vocational qualifications acknowledged as occupationally-oriented by the relevant national authorities and/or the labour market.

indicator_name: Total inbound internationally mobile students, female (number)
long_definition: Total number of female students who have crossed a national or territorial border for the purpose of education and are now enrolled in tertiary institutions outside their country of origin.

indicator_name: Total inbound internationally mobile students, both sexes (number)
long_definition: Total number of students who have crossed a national or territorial border for the purpose of education and are now enrolled in tertiary institutions outside their country of origin.

indicator_name: Inbound mobility rate, both sexes (%)
long_definition: Number of students from abroad studying in a given country, as a percentage of the total tertiary enrollment in that country.

indicator_name: Total net enrolment rate, primary, gender parity index (GPI)
long_definition: Ratio of female total net enrolment rate for primary to the male total net enrolment rate for primary. It is calculated by dividing the female value for the indicator by the male value for the indicator. A GPI equal to 1 indicates parity between females and males. In general, a value less than 1 indicates disparity in favor of males and a value greater than 1 indicates disparity in favor of females.

indicator_name: Total outbound internationally mobile tertiary students studying abroad, all countries, both sexes (number)
long_definition: Students who have crossed a national or territorial border for the purpose of education and are now enrolled outside their country of origin.

indicator_name: Out-of-school adolescents of lower secondary school age, both sexes (number)

indicator_name: Out-of-school rate for children of primary school age, both sexes (%)
long_definition: The number of students of the official age for primary education is subtracted from the total population of the same age. The result is expressed as a percentage of the population of the official age for primary education. For more information, consult the UNESCO Institute of Statistics website: http://www.uis.unesco.org/Education/

indicator_name: Out-of-school rate for children of primary school age, female (%)

The result is expressed as a percentage of the female population of the official age for primary education. For more information, consult the UNESCO Institute of Statistics website: http://www.uis.unesco.org/Education/

indicator_name: Out-of-school rate for adolescents of lower secondary school age, both sexes (%)
long_definition: Number of adolescents of official lower secondary school age who are not enrolled in lower secondary school expressed as a percentage of the population of official lower secondary school age.

indicator_name: Out-of-school rate for adolescents of lower secondary school age, female (%)

indicator_name: Out-of-school rate for adolescents of lower secondary school age, male (%)

indicator_name: Population of the official entrance age to primary education, both sexes (number)
long_definition: Population of the age-group theoretically corresponding to the official entrance age to primary education. The official entrance age is the age at which students would enter a given programme or level of education assuming they start at the official entrance age for the lowest level of education, study full-time throughout and progressed through the system without repeating or skipping a grade. The theoretical entrance age to a given programme or level is typically, but not always, the most common entrance age.

indicator_name: Population of the official entrance age to primary education, female (number)
long_definition: Female population of the age-group theoretically corresponding to the official entrance age to primary education. The official entrance age is the age at which students would enter a given programme or level of education assuming they start at the official entrance age for the lowest level of education, study full-time throughout and progressed through the system without repeating or skipping a grade. The theoretical entrance age to a given programme or level is typically, but not always, the most common entrance age.

indicator_name: School age population, post-secondary non-tertiary education, both sexes (number)
long_definition: Population of the age-group theoretically corresponding to post-secondary non-tertiary education as indicated by theoretical entrance age and duration.

indicator_name: School age population, post-secondary non-tertiary education, female (number)
long_definition: Female population of the age-group theoretically corresponding to post-secondary non-tertiary education as indicated by theoretical entrance age and duration.

indicator_name: School age population, post-secondary non-tertiary education, male (number)
long_definition: Male population of the age-group theoretically corresponding to post-secondary non-tertiary education as indicated by theoretical entrance age and duration.

indicator_name: School life expectancy, primary and secondary, both sexes (years)
long_definition: Number of years a person of school entrance age can expect to spend within the specified level of education. For a child of a certain age a, the school life expectancy is calculated as the sum of the age specific enrolment rates for the levels of education specified. The part of the enrolment that is not distributed by age is divided by the school-age population for the level of education they are enrolled in, and multiplied by the duration of that level of education. The result is then added to the sum of the age-specific enrolment rates. A relatively high SLE indicates greater probability for children to spend more years in education and higher overall retention within the education system. It must be noted that the expected number of years does not necessarily coincide with the expected number of grades of education completed, because of repetition. Since school life expectancy is an average based on participation in different levels of education, the expected number of years of schooling may be pulled down by the magnitude of children who never go to school. Those children who are in school may benefit from many more years of education than the average.

A GPI equal to 1 indicates parity between females and males. In general, a value less than 1 indicates disparity in favor of males and a value greater than 1 indicates disparity in favor of females.

indicator_name: Survival rate to Grade 4 of primary education, both sexes (%)
long_definition: Percentage of a cohort of students enrolled in the first grade of primary education in a given school year who are expected to reach grade 4, regardless of repetition. Divide the total number of students belonging to a school-cohort who reached each successive grade of primary education by the number of students in the school-cohort i.e. those originally enrolled in the first grade of primary education, and multiply the result by 100. The survival rate is calculated on the basis of the reconstructed cohort method, which uses data on enrolment and repeaters for two consecutive years.

The survival rate is calculated on the basis of the reconstructed cohort method, which uses data on enrolment and repeaters for two consecutive years.

indicator_name: Teachers in lower secondary education, both sexes (number)
long_definition: Total number of teachers in public and private lower secondary education institutions (ISCED 2). Teachers are persons employed full time or part time in an official capacity to guide and direct the learning experience of pupils and students, irrespective of their qualifications or the delivery mechanism, i.e. face-to-face and/or at a distance. This definition excludes educational personnel who have no active teaching duties (e.g. headmasters, headmistresses or principals who do not teach) and persons who work occasionally or in a voluntary capacity in educational institutions.

long_definition: Total number of female teachers in public and private lower secondary education institutions (ISCED 2). long_definition: Age at which students would enter early childhood education.

indicator_name: Official entrance age to upper secondary education (years)
long_definition: Age at which students would enter upper secondary education, assuming they had started at the official entrance age for the lowest level of education, had studied full-time throughout and had progressed through the system without repeating or skipping a grade.

indicator_name: Official entrance age to post-secondary non-tertiary education (years)
long_definition: Age at which students would enter post-secondary education, assuming they had started at the official entrance age for the lowest level of education, had studied full-time throughout and had progressed through the system without repeating or skipping a grade.

indicator_name: Theoretical duration of early childhood education (years)
long_definition: Number of grades (years) in early childhood education.

indicator_name: Theoretical duration of post-secondary non-tertiary education (years)
